Air China, BYD, HSBC, Tencent, Zijin: Hong Kong Stock Preview

-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 
2011-07-07T00:05:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-07/air-china-byd-hsbc-tencent-zijin-hong-kong-stock-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the close yesterday.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 1 percent to 22,517.55. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, fell 1.9 percent to 12,598.34.  Oil stocks: Crude oil climbed as much as 0.6 percent today
after the  American Petroleum Institute  said inventories dropped
3.2 million barrels to 357.1 million last week.  PetroChina Co. (857 HK), the nation’s largest oil company,
sank 0.4 percent to HK$11.52.  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  (883 HK) lost 0.5
percent to HK$18.30.  Gold producers: Gold futures for August delivery rose 1.1
percent to settle at $1,529.20 an ounce at 1:43 p.m. on the
Comex in  New York  yesterday.  Zijin Mining Group Co. (2899 HK), which explores for gold
and other  mineral resources , was unchanged at HK$4.08.  BYD Co. (1211 HK): The automaker part-owned by  Warren Buffett ’s Berkshire Hathaway Inc. said its June vehicle sales
fell 8 percent from a year earlier to 32,515 units. The shares
dropped 3.2 percent to HK$26.05.  China Eastern Airlines Corp. (670 HK): China’s top economic
planning body approved plans by the carrier to bring in 16
airplanes into the country through overseas financing, according
to a statement on the National Development and Reform
Commission’s website. The stock lost 0.6 percent to HK$3.47.  Air China Ltd. (753)  (753 HK), the nation’s biggest international
carrier by market value, received approval to bring in nine
airplanes, the NDRC said in a separate statement. Its shares
slid 3.9 percent to HK$7.82.  China Shipping Development Co. (1138 HK): The company which
ships oil and coal won China Securities Regulatory Commission
approval to issue as much as 3.95 billion yuan ($610 million) of
convertible bonds. The shares advanced 0.1 percent to HK$7.41.        HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  (5 HK):  Europe ’s biggest bank plans to
raise the interest rate for mortgages linked to the Hong Kong
interbank offered rate today. The lender will increase the
Hibor-linked mortgage rate to 1.8 percentage point to 2.3
percentage points over Hibor, from 1.5 percentage point to 2
percentage points over Hibor, HSBC said in an e-mailed statement
yesterday. The bank’s shares declined 0.6 percent to HK$77.75.  Tencent Holdings Ltd. (700)  (700 HK): China’s biggest Internet
company agreed to buy a 15.7 percent stake in Kingsoft Corp.
from its executives for HK$892 million ($115 million) to expand
in computer security services, according to a Kingsoft filing to
Hong Kong’s stock exchange yesterday. The deal is scheduled to
be completed today, Kingsoft said. Tencent’s stock fell 0.2
percent to HK$214.60.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shani Raja in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editors responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 